{{Quote|I'm going to freeze my choobies off."<br />"There are easier ways to switch genders, you know."<br />"I didn’t mean I ''wanted'' to freeze 'em off. I just meant–it's ''so cold''.|[[Thane Kyrell]] complaining to [[Dak Ralter]] about the frozen climate of [[Hoth]]|<ref name="Lost Stars">''[[Lost Stars]]''</ref>}}
'''Choobies''' was a slang term for testicles.<ref name="Lost Stars" /> It was also used as a metaphor for courage and confidence: After downing a glass of [[Port in a Storm]], [[Greer Sonnel]] proudly asked, "How's that for choobies?"<ref name="Bloodline">[[Bloodline (novel)|''Bloodline'']]</ref> 

The phrase "pain in the choobies" referred to someone that is very annoying.<ref name="Last Stand 3">[[Battle of Jakku — Last Stand 3|''Battle of Jakku — Last Stand'' 3]]</ref>

{{Stub}}

==Behind the scenes==
The word "choobies" is akin to the vulgar real-world term "balls," which in a literal sense refers to testicles, but is also used as a rude term for bravery and self-assurance.<ref>{{WebCite|url=https://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/english/balls|text=balls|quote=offensive (…) a rude word for testicles (…) a rude word for courage and confidence|work=[[Wikipedia:Cambridge University Press and Assessment|''Cambridge Dictionary'']]|archivedate=20250706154549}}</ref>

"Pain in the choobies"<ref name="Last Stand 3" /> is similar to the real-world offensive idiom "pain in the ass/butt."<ref>{{WebCite|url=https://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/english/pain-in-the-ass-butt|text=a pain in the ass/butt|quote=''idiom'' US offensive (UK '''pain in the arse/backside''') someone or something that is very annoying|work=[[Wikipedia:Cambridge University Press and Assessment|''Cambridge Dictionary'']]|archivedate=20230216013148}}</ref>

